  <section xml:id="intro"><info><title>Setting up the Work directory</title></info>

<para>Go to your home directory
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> cd ~</screen>
Make a directory called Work inside it.  (This is ~/Work)
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> mkdir Work</screen>
Go into the Work directory
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> cd Work</screen>
Make a shortcut (a symbolic link) to the examples directory
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> ln -s ~/local/share/bali-phy/examples</screen>
Take a look inside the examples directory
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> ls examples</screen>
Take a look at an input file
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> less examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta</screen>
Take a look at an input file
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> alignment-info examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta</screen>
</para>

  </section>
<section xml:id="intro"><info><title>Command line options</title></info>

<para>
What version of bali-phy are you running?  When was it compiled?  Which compiler?  For what computer type?
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy -v</screen>
Look at the list of command line options
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy --help </screen>
Look at them with the ability to scroll back
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy --help | less</screen>
Some options have a short form which is a single letter
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy -h | less</screen>
Analyze a data set for 0 iterations.  This is useful to know if the analysis works, what model will be used,
compute likelihoods, etc.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy --show-only examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta </screen>
Finally, run an analysis!  (This is just 10 iterations, so its not a real run.)
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta --iterations=10</screen>
If you specify --imodel=none, then the alignment won't be estimated, and indels will be ignored (just like MrBayes).
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta --iterations=10 --imodel=none</screen>
You can specify the alphabet, substitution model, insertionn/deletion model, etc.
Defaults are used if you don't specify.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta --iterations=10 --alphabet=DNA --smodel=TN --imodel=RS07 </screen>
You can change this to the GTR, if you want.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta --iterations=10 --alphabet=DNA --smodel=GTR --imodel=RS07 </screen>
You can add gamma[4]+INV rate heterogeneity.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/5d.fasta --iterations=10 --alphabet=DNA --smodel=GTR+gamma[4]+INV --imodel=RS07</screen>
</para>

<para>
When the data set contains amino acids, the default is amino acids.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/EF-Tu/12d.fasta --iterations=10</screen>

What alphabet is used here?  What substitution model?
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/HIV/chain-2005/env-clustal-codons.fasta --show-only</screen>
What happens when trying to use the M0 model (e.g. positive selection)?
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/HIV/chain-2005/env-clustal-codons.fasta --show-only --smodel=M0 </screen>
What happens here?
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/HIV/chain-2005/env-clustal-codons.fasta --show-only --smodel=M0 --alphabet=Codons </screen>
</para>

<para>
Try running a few more iterations, but with a fixed alignment so that it will be faster.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/25-muscle.fasta --iterations=100 --imodel=none &#38;</screen>
Run another copy of the same analysis.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/25-muscle.fasta --iterations=100 --imodel=none &#38;</screen>
Look at what output files are produced.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> ls</screen>
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> ls 25-muscle-1/</screen>
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> ls 25-muscle-2/</screen>
See if you can determine the following information from the beginning of the C1.out file:
What command was run?
When was it run?
Which computer was it run on?
Which directory was it run in?
Which directory contains the output files?
What was the process id (PID) of the running bali-phy program?
What random seed was used?
What was the input file?
What alphabet was used to read in the file?
What substitution model was used to analyze the file?
What insertion/deletion model was used to analyze the file?
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> less 25-muscle-1/C1.out</screen>
Examine some of the parameters sampled from the running chain.
If you are using Linux, do % tracer 25-muscle-1/C1.p 25-muscle-2/C1.p
Otherwise, find these files in your file browser, and drag them onto Tracer to open them.
Or run tracer, and press the '+' icon to add files, and select them.

What kind of ESS do you get?
</para>

<para>
Try running a few more iterations, but with a fixed alignment so that it will be faster.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/25.fasta --iterations=200 --imodel=none &#38;</screen>
Run another copy of the same analysis.
<screen><prompt>%</prompt> bali-phy examples/5S-rRNA/25.fasta --iterations=200 --imodel=none &#38;</screen>
Look at what output files are produced.
</para>

